d I was at school. And - I don't know how many years. And there was a - I should think would be about ten or - ten happen and next door's was an old lady, well it was my wife's grandmother used to live next door to us, and she used to knock at the door ha
lf past seven, 'cos they used to have to go to work at six, and she used to knock on the door at half past seven and we used to come down and she'd left our - in the pots - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3302408\charrsid13178822 cocoa}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822  and milk and sugar and the kettle was on the hob, all we had to do was to pour the water onto this and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 This was to make sure you got up for school was it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
Yes, well she got - she just rapped on the door and got us up and saw we were up you know and then we - we - got off to school, I think before the - they used to com
e home probably. They used to work at six 'til eight. Come home for half an hour for breakfast. So probably we'd be home for when they came home for breakfast and then get off. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 There wasn't much difference in your ages?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Not to my brother. Only two years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Do you remember doing anything for each other, to help each other out, little jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
Well he was, I can remember as - he was - he wasn't so good at - at walking at the beginning. He didn't walk for a long time. He must have been a 
rather a - ailing child I think and - can remember mother saying that grandmother used to come and rub him all over with olive oil and she used to say, never give up, never give up home and - and I think he must have been, you know, a bit of a }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3302408\charrsid13178822 weakling}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 . An
d he didn't walk until the was three and I can remember saying to them, he's running mother. He was - he didn't - he hadn't walked, he used to creep about you know - with all - but this time when I saw him he was running from a chair to a chair, straight 
way. And anyway he became a lot - much bigger than I. You - you wouldn't know him would you? He was a big fellow, lived at - up Staymaker Lane, you know, where merchants is. And -
