Not really, no, I once had a pigeon but it didn't do - I didn't have it long. I don't remember having any pets - I don't have any pets - only a cat. That I was very fond of.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 That was a family pet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes, yes. That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did you collect anything such as stamps or cigarette cards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
No. Oh, cigarette cards. And - used to save cigarette cards and you - you used to - you used to know about cigarette cards Mrs Cryer? Used to be in all cigarette and there were - 
there was - in all packets, you know, a series, you could collect series. And also that used to be in football cards. You bought lucky packets and there was one in and it used to be various football clubs. We saved them up to get something. I used to save
 those. And - tors they used to save, used to get a bagful of tors and swop one another for bright marbles and things like that. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did you do any gardening, did you help your father at the allotment?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 No, no, never did. I never - I don't know w
hy I - when I think back you know of me father, he used to go up there and I never thought - dreamt to go and help him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did you ever go fishing or for walks or bicycling?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 I'd go for walking but I didn't go fishing. I only used to go - I loved walking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 You never had a bicycle?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 No, I never had a bicycle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 When you went walks who would you go with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 A cousin of mine, we were friends together and - we went - we used to go - and sometimes with others as well but generally with him
. Yes, for walking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Would you go long walks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Oh we used to walk - well of course it's - what age are you thinking about now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 When you were at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 At school? Oh well, just round by Cuckoo Beck, you know, do you know where - do you 
know where that is? Opposite - you turn - there's a style off a - opposite the cemetery gates. Opposite the public cemetery gates. We used to go down there towards Newsholmes, follow that stream up, looking for birds nests and things like that, right up t
o Tillit Hall, round about the village like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 It was very good for bird watching up there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did you ever take part in any sports at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 No, only the sports connected with the games - you know, the walking days, the galas and so but - racing and things like that, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did you ever go to any theatres at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
Theatres? I can remember father taking us - taking us first time to a pantomime at Keighley. And I thought that was wonderful - it was like }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8079967\charrsid13178822 fairyland}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid818746\charrsid13178822  to me t
hen. I should think I'd be about - perhaps ten or eleven. And I can remember him taking us the first time we saw - a cinematograph you know. That was in Russell Street. But you - before that we only see - saw magic lanterns, still shots you know, this was
 the first time we saw moving pictures they called it, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 How old would you be when you started going to the cinema?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 We went to - that was the first visit with me father, well I'd be - maybe about ten or eleven happen - ten. Then of course as p
ictures became more frequent we used - when I get eleven or twelve we used to go every Saturday you know. And then as - as I came to Howarth I used to go to Howarth at Tuesday as well.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 You never went to any concerts or music halls or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
Not - not in - not when I was young, as I got older I went to British National Opera Company at Bradford you know. But that was when I was in me twenties. Then other concerts, they used to have - give works like Elijah and Messiah and things like
 that and - I didn't often go to that but on a Sunday night there used to be a special singer - that was on a Saturday and on the Sunday they'd have a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8079967\charrsid13178822 sacred}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid818746\charrsid13178822  concert they called it. And I used to go to them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did your parents give you any pocket money before leaving school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
I think we used to get a ha'penny of a Saturday. And - I suppose it got to be a penny sometimes. I - up 'til - up 'to going in the Army - the less pocket money I can remember getting it was half a crown, I used to get half a cr
own a week then. I only had - that was when I was starting at the Co-op, we used to have - I think; a shilling work and a shilling with a bonus I think. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 But before leaving school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 When I went to school I just had - used to have a ha'penny o
n a Saturday. But mother provided us with sweets or fruit to go to school with in the morning and afternoon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 What would you spend it on, can you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Ha'penny, there used to be a shop on the Lane - Church Street and one down Commercial Street and they had lucky bags or }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8079967\charrsid13178822 Spanish}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7219079\charrsid13178822 ?}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
 or - all that sort of things you know you can get for a ha'penny, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did you get it every week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Oh yes, you got it every Saturday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did anyone outside the home help your mother look after her house or family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 You never had any relatives come in to help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 No. We Never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Or friends?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 If your mother was ill, can you remember her ever being ill or confined to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes, in the later years - yes, I can, she were 
- she - I can remember as a child being - her being ill. But not for putting to bed - but I mean once had to stay off from school to be with her all the time. She was laid on the settle you know. But I think it turned - I think she - it turned out to be a
nyhow, blood pressure, high blood pressure in the end that's what she died from, and - must have been that at the time you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 How did she manage, did she manage to do the work herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did someone come in to help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 I only know -
 remember one time in about 1920 when they had to get - she had to go to bed and we had to get somebody in but - normally it was the women and between us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Your parents did have relatives living quite nearby didn't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes. Yes. Especially her sister, mother's sister.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 How much did you see of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
Oh we see - I saw me - mother's sister, me aunt - practically every night, she was down - she - no, me mother'd do her washing and she'd come down and help with the ironing at Monday nights.
 You see. She generally come down and wait for me uncle up there. And then I saw quite a lot of me father's sister that lived top of Providence there. And me other cousins, yes, I saw quite a lot for the family, you know, especially the Oakworth ones.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 You'd see them at your house mainly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Well, both. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7219079\charrsid13178822 
Both, Yes, especially - yes, we went to - used to go - me mother, me father I suppose and me uncle a would be at the club on a - on Saturday night, and me and me mother and aunt and me brother we'd go
 on to Haggas' Falls, it was then, where the garage is, and their children, we played in the Fall and mother and aunt was gassing, you know, was gossiping about - and then when the fathers come home we went home. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 It was quite frequently.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did your parents have friends other than relatives?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes. They had some - a very - they'd one particular - one couple in particular that they used to.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Where did they see them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 They used to see them fairly regularly and then they went to live in Keighle
y at Fell lane. But he was a member of this Oddfellowes club and every night when it was club night they both used to come up and - and of course the mend' go to the club and the women stay at home if I remember. All have supper together afterward.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 So they shared the same friends would you say?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did your mother have any friends of her own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
Well only about this - Miss Coates's where she used to slip up for - regularly, that was her - her girlhood friend, you know, she'd had from a girl, and a neighbour, but I don't think any other no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did Miss Coates come and see her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
No, never, I never remembered her coming to our house. They were - maiden ladies. None of them had been married. And - they used to have a confectionary
 business, they used to be a bit of baking and that sort of thing. They never went out much anywhere, and they certainly never came to our house but she - if she didn't go up she used to - say - they'd be saying, I thought you'd have been coming up, you -
 now, they was expecting here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 They'd be disappointed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes, if she didn't come up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did your father have any friends of his own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 No, only his friends at the mill, he were friendly with the men at the mill you know, the men he worked with. And at the club you know.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Where would he see them, at the club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
At the club and the - at the mill you know, they - that - while they were waiting to go into the mill there used to be a lot standing outside, you know, talking together, the men.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Were friends invited into the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 You told me about these two that used to come in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 About Mr and Mrs Hodgin I were talking about, yes, they used to come in. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Would they be offered anything to eat or drink?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes, yes, they all - when they came up this - to pay this - this club night as you call it they always had a - a supper, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Would you say that the friends invited in were mainly your mother's friends or your father's friends or friends of both?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
Oh this - this two were both. Well, I should think - no, the man'd be me father's friend first. And then his wife and my mother got on well together like so it - it became mutual.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did friends ever call in casually without an invitation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Oh yes. 
When - women that - worked with my mother you know, from when she was at mill, when they were passing they would call in, yes. We nearly always had somebody in the evenings, yes, but - cousins or aunts or something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did your parents ever go out to visit friends or neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Well me mother used to go out to hers but I don't think me father did much visiting.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 What about this couple who came up to the Oddfellowes, would they go and visit them at their house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Oh yes. Well they did when they were in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7219079\charrsid13178822 Oak worth}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 . But not - I don't think - not much when they went to Keighley. They lived in Fell Lane afterwards, but when they lived in Oakworth we used to visit them, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 People often tell us that in those days they made their own
 amusements, what do you think your parents did when they got together with their friends or neighbours, would they make music or have games or just talk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7219079\charrsid13178822 Well I can remember a right together the family when, when me grandma died, I was only young an
d they had a - they - I know they had a wagonette trip to take them to Nelson to see her before she died, you know, the family they got this wagonette. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
I can remember, it must have been at - after the funeral I think, and we was at me uncles and they'd a l
arge family and they'd some friends. And all the children were in the back, it was a double house, all the aunts and uncles were in the front room. All talking. We were all playing games in the back, so - that's - that - I don't know - that's how they wer
e, they were all sat in there discussing things. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 When your parents had friend visiting them would they ever make music, would they even sing or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Not to Mr and Mrs Hodgson didn't but - the - uncles would. When - when we were - when 
were get together you know they would sing and especially at me uncle George because they had a piano and - they were singing chorus's and one - one'd sing and one'd do something else. They'd make us sort entertainments like that. I mean, uncle came from 
London and that, they'd all - they'd all meet together at one of the houses in Oakworth.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Would they ever play games all together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes. The old people - the parents - the parents you mean don't you? We did at me aunts at Christmas yes. We all used to play at -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
Many people divide society into different social classes or groups, in that time before 1918 did you think of some people belonging to one and some to another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Well I suppose I did really I suppose - I used to think - that the - Mr
 Haggas and Hansoms and the vicar and - people like that were in the better class. But me mother used to say that me grandma who'd lived in London you know, said none of these people were gentry. Yes, I suppose they're all manufacturers people. I suppose 
s
he'd probably been in - service of - well nobility I think perhaps. But she wasn't respectful to them but she said they weren't - you know, they weren't - they were none - not the true gentry. Not what shed call gentry. But I used to think they were. The 
Manor people and the Greenfield and - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7219079\charrsid13178822 Hanson\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
 Mill owners and - the vicar and the vicarage - where they had governesses and maids and that sort of thing didn't you. I used to look up to the schoolmaster as well and I used to think they were a class higher you know and that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Could you tell me what the different classes were, you said there were these sort of upper class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes. Well, from my point of view yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 What other classes were there would you say?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Well there'd be the working - I sh
ould think - I should think we were the working class, I should think that, mother and father went to the mill. Then I should think there were people like there was - worked in the office at the mill, cashiers and - people of that sort of way would be a -
 another strata of people that had a bit - where a bit better off.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 They'd be sort of in between?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes, I should think so, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 What sort of people belonged to the same class as yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 The working class family? What jobs did they do?
 Practically everybody worked at the mill you know Mrs Cryer and when you was - when you were at school - I - they the overlooker - when he - when they got to know you, the boy about coming on for twelve they'd be saying to you, you're having a boy coming
 on. And unless you were going to grammar school or something like that they'd expect you to come to the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7219079\charrsid13178822 mill}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
. So practically everybody went to the mill. And if you worked in a shop or in an office well you were that little bit - better, yes. I should think the lowest class were the - you know the working class were - the people that went to the mill.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 You've already told me what other people belonged to the other classes, the teachers and so on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes. The people that teach you. Clerks and shop people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Can you remember being brought up to treat people of one sort differently from people of another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
I don't think so - me mother wasn't snobbish or anything like that, she'd no - no disparagement. She did - she did teach us to respect the vicar and - Mr Arthur, the mill owner.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Mr Arthur Haggas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
Mr Arthur Haggas yes. There was Mr Arthur and Mr James Henry. He lived at the Mill. And she wouldn't like us to be - show any disrespect to them like. But - they - I don't - they weren't servi
le with it or anything like that, just - just thought that you know. 'Course they had - they were - had your life in their hands in a sense in that they employed 'em didn't they. That's right, they did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Were you taught to raise your cap or show respect in some way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 I wasn't, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Was there anyone that you called sir or madam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Used to call the vicar sir and the schoolmaster. And - we used to call the teacher Miss Mann. But I don't think anybody else, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Do you remember anyone showing respect to your parents in these ways?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 No. No, no. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Such as touching their cap to them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 It was very uncommon thing to do in - in the village at that time, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 In the village who were considered the most important people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
In the village? I should say Haggas's and Sugdens, you know, that had the - the mill and - and that, Attersleys, Newsholmes and - people that - mill owners generally. And then you get the doctor and the vicar. And to a lesser extent the Baptist mi
nisters I suppose. Then there's some - one or two - Miss Cockshotts lived at Wildfell, they were - sort of gentry. Miss Cockshotts. And the Berwins, they used to have - you know that - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7219079\charrsid13178822 
shuttle making}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822  place at Fernside, but it was Berwins before that, before them. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7219079\charrsid13178822 
Yes, they lived in them houses - there's Sosselnest isn't there, the top of Lidgett now there's Bank House and Surrey Bank. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 All those three houses }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7219079\charrsid13178822 were}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822  built, different Berwin brothers lived in them. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Why would you say these people were considered important?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
Well I don't know really unless it's - they lived in bigger houses and - and were obviously employers of labour and I suppose we thought they must be well off. Think it was put down to wealth and their positions generally. But gen
erally speaking looking back at they were very nice people, they didn't treat anybody ask - dirt or anything. They were very friendly I think as a whole. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Could you tell me who you think the following people would associate with, who would be thei
r friends, the shopkeepers, who would they associate with mainly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
Well - I think they more or less - well, there used to be the two brothers at the Post office and the tailor next door and they always went about together and then - there was another tailor up }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7219079\charrsid13178822 Lidgett}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 . I think shopkeepers seemed to kind of get together as a whole you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Who would the clergy be friends with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Now I don't know that. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7219079\charrsid13178822 
The vicar used to be friendly with Mr Arthur Haggas and James Henry at the Manor and - don't know about the Methodist ministers where they - they probably be friendly with the Berwins and people like that attended their chapels you know. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Berwins were - attended the - they're all mostly at Slack Lane.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 So the clergy associated with the top class people who went to their respective churches?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Oh - yes, I should think so, yes, that's right.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Who would the teachers associate with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Well there weren't many teachers lived in Oakworth, the schoolmaster lived in Oakworth. And - him and h
is wife were very - withdrawn. I don't think they associated much with }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7219079\charrsid13178822 anybody}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
. And the women teachers nearly all came from about Keighley or Bingley or somewhere like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 So you don't know who they were friends with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 What about the farmers in the district?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
Farmers? Well I - I know the boys - boys used to come to church school you know from the farms around and they more or loss congregated together. Used to see 'em when they came down with the milk - milk to the station and 
see 'em at - when I got to the shop you know, working in the shop they used to come down bringing their butter to sell and that sort of thing. I should think they were sort of - well I'll tell - and then they come to the corn mill you know. And - more or 
less they were a self contained community.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Just friends together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Just all the farmers, they met at these places when they were doing business.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 They were quite isolated farms weren't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes. Quite a lot yes. Butter used to come to the shops and eggs and that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Who would the employers be friends with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
The employers? Berwins - oh aye, Berwins and that. Well, I think - Mr - Haggas's - Mr Arthur was very withdrawn - he lived - his wife had died before I was born so he'd had a s
hort and happy married life and she died very early without - leaving him without children, and he didn't go out very much at all. Then he had a nice come to live with him. His wife's }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7219079\charrsid13178822 niece}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 . And - and then there was the - these - I think the Newsholmes - I
 know the Newsholmes and the - them that live at Withins used to be very friendly with them at the manor. And so I suppose they did kept very much to theirselfs like that. I don't think Mr Arthur had much social life at all. And of course they Haggas fami
ly branched into Keighley. There's Alice Haggas's and Haggas's at Keighley, it's all the same family. But it came to an end in this - this branch when Mr Arthur died.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 This was a separate branch?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 They were all from the same father. There used to b
e the two engines in that big engine room. One was called William and one was called Sarah, and that was - the founder of the family - William and Sarah Haggas.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 The engines were called after them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Who would you say they mixed with, you say Mr Arthur didn't mix with anybody?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
They - I don't think so. I know the vicar used to visit him and people like that. And when I was a little boy up at Bridge Street I can remember 'em having dinner parties on occasions 'cos I remember me mother
 going in to help - and carriages coming up and that. But I don't think he had much social life, I don't think he mixed - I don't think he went out much at all but - they were the first to have a car in Oakworth. Yes, they had - his }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7219079\charrsid13178822 niece}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822  used to drive the
m, they'd two cars. And - he used to go to Bradford. Because you see, he'd mix with - he used - they used to always go to Bradford to the - for wool market on a Thursday. So he'd mix there wouldn't he, Mr }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7219079\charrsid13178822 Arthur}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822  always went there, she used to drive him there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 What about the other employers, would they be friends with each other or with people from another place or people in the village?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 You mean - the other mill owners? I should - I should imagine though Mrs Cryer, they'd meet at this market woul
dn't they. The wool market, the wool - the wool manufacturers. They used to go to market every Thursday at Bradford, the wool - is it closed now the wool? Wool Exchange yes. So they used to go so they'd all meet there wouldn't they. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 What sort of people would you say went to the church at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
Oakworth church has never had a lot of better class - Mr Arthur used to support it with his money but he never came, very seldom, only on a funeral or something like that. He was a good benefactor
 to us. But - Han - Hansoms used to come and the - the better class that did come they came at Sunday morning at half past ten. And people had somebody else at home who could cook the dinner you see. But most like mother and people that had families, then
 they came in the evening. Chiefly working class people. If there was any better class they were there in the morning and - and the others was in the evening.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 What about the chapel, what sort of people went to the chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Oh, much the same I shou
ld think. Yes, much the same - you know, they're all mill people and - perhaps - Berwins of course were good - good people to this Baptist. Yes, the Baptist at Slack Lane. Miss Cockshotts was - very keen about the Wesleyans. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7219079\charrsid13178822 Oh and Sugdens, Percy Sugdens down at the Vale Mill they had to go to church - chapel on Sunday, they worked there, yes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Said so, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 That was a condition of employment was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 I think it was almost expected to do anyway, yes. And of course Sir Isaac Holden }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7219079\charrsid13178822 built}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822  that chape
l, this one before this - before - the old one, yes. And they were supporters of the chapel. I think really the Wesleyans were the strongest - well they were in the field first I think. Oakworth church was - only built in - 1846. And 1844 the school. And 
the chapel is - considerably a bit older. There's an older one than - that }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7219079\charrsid13178822 Isaac}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822  built - before Sir }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7219079\charrsid13178822 Isaac}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822  Holden built there was one before that I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 The Methodist chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes, that's right. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Where you lived did all the people in the
 working class have the same standard of living or would you say that there were different groups within the working class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Oh yes. Well I should think so except in he cases where you - in the cases where you - say there's large families, it was - th
ey didn't have quite much fancies you know, it was more plain living. More plain living the bigger the family was I suppose, yes. But otherwise more or less the same standard, yes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7219079\charrsid13178822 
but you - you stood a better chance if there was only two of you, you know.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Were some families thought of as rough and others as respectable?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
Just occasionally, not many I don't think. It was - if it was it was in a case of the father was a drinker. And they tended to be neglected you know. But there weren't many but there were a few I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Do you remember a distinction of this kind between craftsmen and labourers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
Craftsmen and labourers? I don't think it applied in the mill that. No, you see, they didn't come much in touch with outdoor labourers much. No,
 I don't think so Mrs Cryer. No. Of course, bosses in the mill like heads of departments, they were a bit higher up you know, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did your mother and father have the same attitude to people in different classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 I think so Mrs Cryer, yes, I never know any - they were - any reason to think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Do you think your mother saw herself as belonging to a particular social class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Mother? No, I don't think so. She was friendly with a lot of them. If she had a set it was people - people at churc
h and where she worked you know, in the drawing. Women with her.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Was it possible at that time to move from one class to another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Very unlikely I should say. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Do you know of anyone who did this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 No. Unless people had started a small business and got up that way you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Do you know of anyone who did that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
Well I should say like - Fernsides and - Berwins and - Finders I should think too, you know, that - but not many, I can't think of many. But that - if they - if they g
ot into the next class it'd be through having a successful business and of course having a very good shop. That sort of got them a step up too. Yes. Finance, and gradually built it - up, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Do you remember anyone being described as a real gentleman or a real lady?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
Oh yes, me mother used to say that many a time. But not only about rich people, she'd say that about - you know, any good woman, she's a real lady. A real gentleman he is. But - not - not in - not in a sense that they were better off 
I mean. 'Cos the character, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 This was because of their character?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes. Mother used that - used that expression. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Do you remember seeing a policeman around where you lived?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Oh yes. Used to - 'cos there was a local - local policeman. Lived in Park Avenue.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 How do you think he treated the people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 I think all right, but you know we were just - he was the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7219079\charrsid13178822 bobby}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 , we used to be a bit scared of him you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 When you were naughty did your mother ever say, I'll call the policeman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
I never - no, I don't think so, no. No, she never threatened us with the policeman. I think it'd be our - I think it'd have been eternal disgrace if the policeman had come to the house for anything. Oh I'm sure it would. Used to be -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Sometimes mothers used to frighten their children by saying they'd tell a policeman didn't they?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes. Yes. I don't think she ever used that. And I know me grandmother was particularly }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7219079\charrsid13178822 frightened}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822  of policemen some reason, mother's mother. Then when sh
e used to live in Mount Pleasant and she went to - an end sort of - stood at the; bottom and she used to - it's not you I'm frightened of, it's your buttons. I know. Some way, I don't know why. Perhaps she'd come from London and seen 'em a bit rough or ha
ppen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Was your home rented?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Rented - oh yes. Belonged to like the firm, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did you see anything - your landlord would be Mr Haggas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did you see anything of your landlord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 No, they had a - they had a - a rent coll
ector came round every Friday for the rent. One of the clerks in the office. And they kept 'em in very good repair you know, they kept it all in good repair and that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 What did you feel about him as a landlord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Well - we always thought of him as 
somebody - I always thought of him as somebody special you know. Yes. We - kept silent when - if he happened to go past.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Do you remember feeling that your parents had to struggle to make ends meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Not generally, I know me mother always had to -
 have this - she frequently had the doctor and of course it - she always seemed to be - have a doctor's bill on. This man - at Friday night they used to have a man come for the doctor's bill and a man for the insurance and a man for the rent. You know, th
ey all - she used to be put out all that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 So you didn't think really that they had to struggle at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 No, well I wouldn't say we were destitute. I might say they were - they wouldn't have anything to spare, they couldn't have could they bu
t - they - they never let us see it if they did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Your father was never out of work through illness was he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 No, only except, you know, at the latter end. He - he was never out of work, just on short time.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 When there was someone in the distr
ict whom the people disapproved of very strongly, was there any special way in which they showed it? Do you remember anyone ever being made to leave by rough music?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 No, I don't Mrs Cryer. Driven out of the place like? No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 You were never given lessons at home were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 No. No. No I didn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 How old were you when you first went to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 I should think about five I think. Four or five.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did you start morning and afternoon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes, started straight away, all full time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 What time in the morning did you go when you started?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 I think we started at nine o'clock didn't it. Yes, nine o'clock to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 What kind of a school was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 A church school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 It was a day school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Mixed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Mixed, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 How did you get to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Walked it - you know, when I go up Bridge Street and Mill Lane. Just on the Lane you know where it is.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 How long did it take you to get there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Oh - take me - take us - five minutes would it. Unless we dawdled playing on but to go there to walk -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Who went with you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Well we - when were very young me brother went but - generally I used to go with a friend of mine. We used to call for one another.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Your mother never took you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Oh no. Even in the first going I can remember one of me older cousins from me uncle's family gook us for the first time I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Where did you have your midday meal then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Where did? Oh came home. Home to it, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 What did you think of school, did you like it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes, I have happy remembrance, yes. I liked it very much, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 How did you feel about the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Oh very fond of them. Yes. Schoolmaster I liked and especially the teacher - woman teacher that used to teach us in the - second and t
hird - used to be perhaps two classes - second and third class about. Yes, I remember her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did the teachers emphasise certain things as important in life, such as manners, tidiness, punctuality or ways of speaking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Very - I can remember - thing 
I - remember most, we always had to have us clogs clean. We were lining up first and you'd to have your clogs shining, yes, you used to get drilled up if you were - and your }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7219079\charrsid13178822 hands}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822  - they used to look at your hands, they used to look at your hands to see if you - if they were dirty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did they insist on you being on time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
Yes. We used to be on time, yes, definitely, when they blow the whistle you had no to be late, to be on time and you'd to have your clogs cleaned and you'd to have your hands clean and generally tidy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 If you did something the teachers disapproved of what would happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7219079\charrsid13178822 Well if it was very bad you got the cane. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 On your hand.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 It was always the cane was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did the girls get the same as the boys?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Y
es. I don't think there were many - we were all in the same class. I don't remember the girls often getting caned. I don't think - I don't know. I suppose perhaps they would but I can't - just can't remember them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 For what offences would it be used?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
No, I - you know, just - insubordination, insisting on talking or anything lie that, I don't think so. I can remember sometime the women teachers'd - parents'd come to see them, I can remember - I can remember parents coming to see the women teachers 
and the women teachers going - having to go out to the porch to see them and then coming back crying. Yes, I can remember - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 They'd be young lady teachers would they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 They were lady - you know, lady - you know, I suppose they'd be about twenty wouldn't they, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 And the parents had said something to them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
There must have been - you know, there was something - some of the girls or something that - father and mother had come down to - and - but they'd go out - they wouldn't ever hav
e them - they'd go out into the porch you know. With the schoolmaster and can remember seeing the teacher coming in - weeping, yes. But I don't - it wasn't general, but it happened sometimes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did your parents show an interest in your schoolwork?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes. But they - they didn't - they wouldn't back us up if we'd been - got into any trouble. Said we deserved it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 They never came to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did they ask you what you did at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes, they were interested. Used to see how we were going on for writing and reading and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did they visit the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 No, I don't think they - I don't - no, they didn't ever visit the school during the school hours, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 They never met the teachers?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes. They never met the teach
ers. They'd now Mr Proctor the schoolmaster because he - they seemed to - the affairs on the Sunday school like.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did the other children come from similar types of home to your own or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes. All - all - you know, mill people or farmers sons.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did the teachers single out some children for different treatment from the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 No, I don't think -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Were there any gangs or groups in the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 No, I don't think so. I was - I should think it'd be too small for that you know, the 
- I don't remember any - you - you had groups of friends you know but - I don't know anything like gangs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Would you say these groups of friends were friends from a certain district?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Well yes, they would you know, be - came from Mill Lane and up 
Bridge Street you know, you naturally gravitated - you were going to school together and coming home the same districts, yes. Like Oakworth was sort of nearly divided. This part of the village was mostly at the church - for the church school. And the othe
r part went to the - it was a - we called a board school in those days you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 That was Station Road?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 That was Station Road, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Would you say that there were any children left out of things when you were at school for one reason or another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 No, I don't think so, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 You can't think of anybody who was a bit isolated?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Anybody was isolated, no I don't think so. I don't remember anything that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 You went to the church school at Oakworth, did you go to another school after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 No, never. I went 'til I was - well I was twelve I went half - half time working, and then I - I left finally when I - was thirteen.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Would you have stayed longer if you had had the opportunity at school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Possibly I would but - they 
were ready for your - your money in the mill. I know particularly my wife, the - schoolmaster asked - begged and begged her parents to let her go to grammar school but they wouldn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 But you had no ideas about staying on any longer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 No, I - no, I hadn't, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did you go for any part time education }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7219079\charrsid13178822 afterwards}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 , evening classes or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
Yes, well I did for a whole. There used to be evening classes at the Holden Hall you know, in the winter. And I went to those once - one season I think. I don't think I went more, but I remember going one winter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 What did you take there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
Mathematics and - literature and horticulture which - they stated - you - you did the theory in the winter then you had a garden - there was school 
gardens in Holden in the summer. You had a plot all to yourself and that. Yes. Where the park is now. You know where the park is. The back there. We used to go there. That was - I think - and there was physical education - physical exercises you know.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did you go three nights a week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
I should think I should - used to go two or three, I can't just remember. I know Monday I think for Mathematics. Then we used to go for - and - and physical. And then the other one I think it was - anyway - probably t
wo nights I think then - I can remember doing Dickens's plays and things like that - Dickens's books. And horticulture, yes, that's right. I think it'd be two - two nights and we did two subjects each night probably.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Do you have any regrets about your education?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
Well I did afterwards you know, when I wanted - when I - you know, when I got on - got older you know. I've learnt more since - I think it set me off, it was an education that set you off interest - became interested in history and - and 
literature and things like that which I read - you know, I started going to the library very early. First I - first before you could go to the public library the Co-op used to have a library at Keighley and they were free - they had a fairly good selectio
n of - for me as I was then anyway, and I used to get them from there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 That was before the Carnegie library?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Well probably the Carnegie was, but when Oakworth was a - an urban district I don't you were - you would - I don't think you-could go to 
that then you know. You see, it was Keighley. Wasn't part of Keighley but it was Oakworth Urban District Council.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Do you think you benefited from attending school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Oh - from attending school - night school or ordinary.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Both.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Both. Ye
s, I do, yes. Well I was put into the way of reading, I could - and I liked reading and an interest in things like that. Although my - you know, I didn't sort of - not so good on arithmetic, I've picked things up since you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Is that why you took maths at night school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
Well I don't think so, not particularly because these were these first subjects you see. And you - you had a small fee to pay and if you went to - you made sufficient attendances you got it back again at the end of the year.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Who was the night school run by?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 It was the West Riding County Council I think. Yes I think so, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 While you were at school did you have a part time job or any means of earning a little extra money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 No, I never did, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 But you started work half time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
At twelve, yes. You went - you went one morning - one week in the mornings, school in the afternoon, and then the opposite next week. School in the morning, work in the afternoon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 What were you doing at work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 I wa
s - offer in the spinning. Worked in the spinning mill. Doffing bobbins off as they were full you know, you went round and - at Haggas's yes. And finally I went - oh, in the end, because the war came on. Does this apply? And then - I'd be about, I stayed 
t
here 'til I was about - must have been about fourteen, the war came on, and the men - and I - they put me in charge of the time office, you know, the - they used to call it the penny hole. And anybody - when - at - supposing the hour - they were left five
 minutes by the doors open and then - and then they were locked. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7219079\charrsid13178822 And that meant everybody had to pass through this you see and - supposed to put their names down.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 So they didn't have a system of clocking in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 They had - they had - they had - yes,
 they had clocks, used to have clocking in - in the different departments. But - it didn't apply to weavers I don't think you see. We just didn't clock in I don't think. But it - but they did - but - they lock the main doors and after - anybody that passe
d through the time office you know they had their name taken and they were fined you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Had you to keep these records of peoples names then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Used to have to put these names down. And I can remember some of the women you know I'd be about fifte
en, with the weavers, you see, you put my name down in that book. Used to be scared stiff off them. I was there about - and then in addition I used to do the - chop firewood for the office and get the tin - they used to pay - have - pay the wages, they us
e
d to give them all checks, a number on a check. And at Thursday I had to take these checks round to the heads of the department. And then in addition they had some big trays with some little tins in and all these tins had to be put in the numbers. And I u
s
ed to do, on Thursday morning I used to be in a place putting these tins in the correct numbers. Then the cashier came and put the money in. And they presented the checks Friday night at the window there. And - I used to to chop wood for them and for - fi
rewood for Greenfield and Ford, the Manor and the office in between times. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 So you started half time as a doffer in the spinning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 How did you manage to get this job, was it through your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Oh yes, they - they w
ere waiting of you. They used to say, you'll have a lad coming on soon haven't you? Say, yes. They expected you to go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 That was at Haggas's?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 That was Haggas's yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 So you were a doffer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes. At four and six a week for half time when y
ou've - when you'd learnt - and - when you were full time eight and six. And then - when the war came on we got a - we got a rise to about eleven and six.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 So you were working mornings one week and afternoons the other week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Alternately, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 What about Saturdays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
Saturdays you worked 'til - twelve o'clock I think. But if you were working mornings, you didn't have to go - Saturday. You went on the afternoons next week. But when you'd been working afternoons you went Saturday morning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 And you got four and six a week did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
It was four and six for half time and when you got to the full wage. And then - and then it got - went up to about eight and six or eleven and six for full time, you know, that was about a fifty hour week wasn't it. Something like that, a full week.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did this job alter your attitude to school at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
Well I think - you know, I missed - I missed school very much I remember and I used to look forward to the half days at school, more than I would - more than I thought would have done. But I gradually got - acclimatized to the working and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 And then you started to work full time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did you stay doffing for a while?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 At thirteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 And you stayed as a doffer did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 I stayed as a doffer until - they put me in charge of this - the time office and these jobs for the office.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 How long would that be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 I left - it'd be - better be in - 19 - early 1915 I think. Because the war - you know, the men had gone to the war in 1914.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 So you were doffing for about two years were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 I recon twelve and thirteen and fourteen, would be good two years wouldn't it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 A year part time and a year full time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes. Twelve.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 And then you went to do this job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 It was the - the same firm you now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 What hours did you work once you started full time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
Six o'clock - six o'clock 'til eight. And then came home for half an hour for breakfast. And then half past eight 'til half past twelve. And then an hour for dinner. And half past one 'til half past five. And twelve o'clock on Saturday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Seven o'clock 'til twelve on Saturday was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Six - six o'clock in the morning. Six - oh yes, used to at mill, always six o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did you ever have to work Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did you get any holidays with pay while you were at Haggas's?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 And you were paid eight and six when you went full time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Well it was eight and six and then it went to eleven and six but when I got this other job 
- job in the time office my father went - thought I - I thought I ought to have some more money. So he asked Mr Arthur and he gave me - I got sixteen shillings. But I'd even to stay meal times, you know, I couldn't - mother had to bring me meals down beca
use I had to be there at lunchtime.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 So that was quite a good wage really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes, very good, yes, sixteen shillings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Before that you'd only got eight and six when you were still doffing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Eleven and six. The final total, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did you give all of the money to your mother or did you keep some yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Money? No, we handed it all over to mother, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 What was it spent on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Then she gave us spending money. I can't remember what we got after we started working. No, I can't 
remember. We always had spending money anyway.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did the rest of the money go into the family budget?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 How did you get on with the other people you worked with when you started work at first?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Well - I - they were - I found it a bit
 rough you know, a bit - after being at school and that you know. Just for a few weeks, but afterwards I settled down and got on all right, yes. Same as I did in the army. I mean to say I found it very rough in the first month or so, then settled down, ye
s. Newness isn't it and - they - they play tricks on you when you go don't they, sort of - when you're new, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 How did you employer treat you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Oh aye, well the - the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1518394\charrsid13178822 over lookers}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid818746\charrsid13178822  at the mill, they were the ones. Well they - I suppose the - they
 had to keep a lot of children in order hadn't they - they used to - I'd be running around you know and - if you didn't do as you were told they gave you a good calling, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 What about Mr Haggas himself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Oh yes, you never saw - no, you didn't come in contact with him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 How did you feel about him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
Well I thought he was - you know, I looked up to him, I thought he was the - the boss you know, and - I used to - he used to occasionally come through the mill and he'd - small man with a - an
d very smart with a orchid and he used to come and smoke a long cigar and it smelt wonderful.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 How did you feel about the work, did you like it or dislike it when you were still doffing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 When - after I'd got - after I'd get settled in and that I 
didn't mind it. Used to have, you know, like a lot of children do together. I can tell you this if you like, about this eleven and sixpence. All the doffers decided we ought to have some more money, when we were getting eight and six and working and we al
l
 decided to go out on strike. And - everybody - they all did except just one or two. And he used come - you know on Mill Lane, the offices, what's offices, at the back there's some steps if you - have you ever noticed? Well he used to come down from Green
f
ield House, he had a private way down there you see. We all stood at the bottom of those steps and - he was a little bit deaf and he walked down come down about - oh I should think there'd be - perhaps forty or fifty of us you know, lot of us, in the thre
e
 rooms, yes. And he was walking past as if it was quite usual you see and somebody plucked up courage to say, Mr Arthur, we want a rise. And - he says, this is no place to get a rise, get back to your works. And somebody else said, please Mr Arthur, we're
 not going back 'til we get a rise. And so we went up to play at the playground I remember the afternoon. Still we got it. We got this eleven and six.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 You spent the rest of the day in the playground did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 You went back to work the day after?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes, the next day, I think, sent word round it was all settled.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 There was no }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1518394\charrsid13178822 retribution}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid818746\charrsid13178822  then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 You quite liked the doffing once you got used to it did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 It was monotonous you know, used to be watching the cl
ock and doing all sorts of things to pass the time you know. And - but of course that passed, put children in the working doesn't it when you first start working. It wasn't - it wasn't hard work and if you got - except for your feet, you know, you were ru
nning up and down and that. Your feet got tired.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 How did you feel about your work once you moved into the time office?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 When? Well I think it was bad for me. I liked it but there was too little to do you know, I was - for a boy at my age, fifteen 
- I got a bit slack I think with - nothing to do and no - nobody over to me so to speak and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 You worked by yourself more or less?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 But you know there was a little sitting about, just sitting there. Well - and - and except for running errands for the office and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Were you sort of office junior?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
I think it was I think and I - I used to put - take the letters to the post and - get insurance stamps and fetch errands for the clerks you know, tobacco and things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 And chopping wood?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 And that - all had to go in to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 This was for the office and Mr Haggas's private house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
Yes, the - and the other one - the Manor. Yes. I used to get the wood from the joiner's shop in the mill you know. And in between time I did that. But - I 
think - I think, you know, I ought to have had a bit more, I was too young to go without supervision, you see, but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 How long did you stay at Haggas's in the time office?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 That would be - I think - I think I'd - I'd only be there about a year. Th
at was - I think it'd be 1915. Well I went to the Co-op in - at - January 1916. So it must have been about a year.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 You went to the Co-op in 1916?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 What made you make this move?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Well I wanted - there was a notice in the - in Lane i
n Co-op and it had been in ever such a long time and they couldn't get anybody, a junior wanted, for Oakworth shops. And I kept on to me mother and wanted to go. Yes. She didn't - they didn't want me to go, and - didn't think I was good enough for the Co-
o
p you know. And - anyway I finally - and they finally let me go. And there was a Mr - used to come - the secretary used to come to that - Oakworth Hall there. there was an office up there. Used to come at Fridays for - you know, transactions, business you
 
know. And I went to see him you know, and he just asked me to write me name and I got the job. And I used to have to do half a day - I worked between Lane Ends and Oakworth Hall. I went half day at one and half day at other and in addition I had to get - 
relieve the managers for their lunches and teatime. So I was continually backwards and forwards. Until 19 - Christmas 1916. They closed that one. Oakworth Hall. 'Cos of lack of staff, you know, they couldn't staff them. And I went to work at }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13459625\charrsid13178822 Lidgett}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Was it by then the same society?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes, it - Oakworth. They used to be separate, yes. But there was Oak - Keighley when I went to work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Was it Oakworth society?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 No, Keighley. Yes, Keighley had taken them all and I've always worked for Keighley, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 So you went to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13459625\charrsid13178822 Lidgett}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid818746\charrsid13178822  and you were there permanently?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 After - I just had that one year between the two - doing the two shops and then I went to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13459625\charrsid13178822 Lidgett}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822  permanently yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 You were a junior at }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13459625\charrsid13178822 Lidgett}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid818746\charrsid13178822  were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 I was junior then but at }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13459625\charrsid13178822 Lidgett}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid818746\charrsid13178822  there was two of us. There was a manager and two - two boys. I think I'd be the elder.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 So you weren't quite the junior at }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13459625\charrsid13178822 Lidgett}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 You were the manager's assistant, you were a proper grocery assistant?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 When you worked between the two you were actually serving in the shops were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 You got it by yourself, you went for this interview?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes, I got permission from me mother. Yes, I think - I went on my own I think, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 What hours did you work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
At that time it used - I think we started at eight o'clock and - seven o'clock most nights, half past seven I think on Wednesdays and nine o'clock on Friday and six o'clock on Saturday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 What time did you start in the morning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Start? I think it was eight o'clock. Yes. I think you had an hour for lunch and half an hour for tea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 So you worked all day Saturday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 'Til six o'clock, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did you ever work Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 No. No, never worked Sunday.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did you have a half day off during the week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Oh - Tuesday afternoon. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did you have any holidays with pay while you worked there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Oh - oh yes, always, from - from starting at the Co-op they always, you know, paid for holidays. All - all the
 year you always had your full wage. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 What were you paid?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Well at first I think it was - I think it was about seven or eight shillings and - and there was a shilling tacked on for war bonus.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 So you had quite a drop in wage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Oh yes
, quite a drop, that's the - that was one of the objections you see. But - it gradually kept up. But do you know, I was there to - at }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13459625\charrsid13178822 Lidgett}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 , until I had to join the Army in 1918. And then it had got up to eighteen shillings. But I think if I had stayed then it was just about - about to jump to twenty-six. There was going to be a big jump.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did they term it some sort of apprenticeship that you did at the Co-op?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 It was apprenticeship, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 And that was why you had such a low wage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 That's right, it was apprentice wage you see, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 So when you went in the Army you would normally have just finished your apprenticeship?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes, well I think - no, I think the apprenticeship really didn't lasted }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13459625\charrsid13178822 
till}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822  you were twenty-one. Yes. Onl
y the - the wages - I know there'd be an increase but I know I just missed it. And consequently with having such a low wage when you went in the army they - at that time they used to give your parents so much pay according to what wage you earned. If you 
h
ad a - if you - if you'd been on the back shop and earning a good wage you got more separation. With me only having about eight, nine shilling me mother only got about three and sixpence. Yes. I know she saved it all up for me and bought a suit when I com
e out. But - it worked like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Once you started at the Co-op did you still give all your money to your mother every week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes. And then I got half a crown back I remember. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 When you were working at the Co-op did you feel you got a fair wage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
Oh yes, I think so, yes. Yes, there was good - there was better conditions than most because there were nowhere else where you got paid for holidays, I don't think so, not - not in - not in the mills anyway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 How did you get on with the other people at the Co-op?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
Oh very well, yes, I'd - different managers and - some of them were stricter than others. Of course because that's natural, you didn't - it didn't appeal to you when you're young but you realize now. And they were all good, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 How did your employer treat you, at the Co-op you don't have an employer as such do you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
It just depends on the manager really doesn't it, yes. Yes, well - I had about - I worked in those different ones, I'd say about one, two, three - at 
least four before I went in the Army and - and I think they - I - I had nothing to complain of or anything no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 How did you feel about the work at the Co-op?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Well - I did at first but I - I used to be - wish I was - had a job where they worked Sa
turday like everybody else. It was working Saturday afternoon that I didn't like.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 You felt it hard?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
Yes, I used to - I used to go on at me mother and that see if I could get back into the mill you know to have Saturday. But wisely enough they didn't let me. No. They didn't - because -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 So you actually asked your mother to get you back in the mill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes. Asked me father to get me back - get me a job in the mill, yes, Saturday. But I liked the Co-op. And I'm glad I didn't go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 What did your mother say at that point?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Oh no, they wouldn't hear of it. Stay, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 So really she was pleased that you'd made the move?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes. Oh yes, I think so. Well I think it was only - I don't know - I think it were chiefly the money really.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 But once you'd made the move she got used to the money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Move, yes. Yes, yes, that's right. Then of course - wages were going up in the mills then, after I left wasn't it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 What made you make this move?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Well it - it was a custom - it was
 a custom you went to the mill until you were about sixteen then you went to learn your trade. All boys did that. They either went to - into shops or into the black shops in Keighley you know and began - became apprentices. They only - most - most boys - 
you all had - had to learn a trade as they called it. So that was the reason really. The matter of choosing which trade to learn.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 And you liked the work at the no-op?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 It was just the Saturday afternoon you didn't like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Then I got accustomed to that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 And you worked for the Co-op doing that same job until you joined the Army in 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes, that's right. In }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13459625\charrsid13178822 Lidgett}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 And you were in the Army until 1919?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 I was in the Army until 1920. I was - I went - I left in - I l
eft the Co-op in October 1918 then I came back again to the Co-op, at the end of March 1920.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 And you worked for the Co-op from then onwards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 In fact you still do work for the Co-op?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 That's right, yes. I've never been out - you kn
ow, except from that period in the Army, that small period when I - that once when I'm - I've been there ever since, ever since 1916.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 You were a shop assistant at }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13459625\charrsid13178822 Lidgett}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid818746\charrsid13178822  branch were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13459625\charrsid13178822 And I came back to Lidgett when I came back, they se
nt me to Lidgett again and I stayed there until - about 1934. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
Then I went to various shops in Keighley as assistant. And then came first - first counterman they used to call it didn't they, at one of the central shops in Keighley. And finally I became a manager at Morton Banks.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 When was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 It's at Riddlested. You know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 But when was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 It was the beginning - just before the war began, 1938. The year of Munich crisis, that very week. Yes, I remember it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 That was your first managing job was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
Yes. And I was there all through the war. 'Til 1946. And which of course it used to be a bit of a struggle getting there and back in the war, you know, the blackout, I used to go in the morning and be away all day and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 You were still living at Oakworth then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Still lived at Oakworth, yes, in George Street, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Where did you move to from Morton Banks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Back to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13459625\charrsid13178822 Lidgett}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 As a manager?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes. I was manager at Morton Banks. And I came to manage }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13459625\charrsid13178822 Lidgett}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 That would be more convenient for you wouldn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Oh yes. They said - they promised to get me nearer home as soon as the - the war was over you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 When was it that you moved back to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13459625\charrsid13178822 Lidgett}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 1946.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 So you were manager at }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13459625\charrsid13178822 Lidgett}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 I was manager at Morton Banks about eight years. And I was manager at }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13459625\charrsid13178822 
Lidgett}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822  from 1946 'til - '65. Yes. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 And then you retired and you were only at home a short while weren't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 About - about eight weeks, about eight or nine months.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 And then you got this job down at the Central Co-op?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Box crushing isn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 That's right, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 You still work, is it still part time the house that you work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Well I go from nine o'clock 'til twelve - 'til four. Just part time it is, definitely part time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Do you work a four day week or five?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Every day, go every day. Saturday I only stay 'til about half past eleven.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 So you're still working quite a full week really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes. Really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Would you have preferred another type of occupation had you your time over again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
No I don't think - you know, with my capabilities I think it - I think the job suited me. Yes, I think it did, I think - - I took to it like a duck to water as they say.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 You served a sort of an apprenticeship, they termed it an apprenticeship didn't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
Yes, I served apprenticeship with them. And of course when I came back it was - they had some sort of a scheme, the government, didn't they - they paid - they paid the society
 so much for the time you had lost of your apprenticeship. Yes, there was some sort of - some papers. They took you back and - they sort of give us some sort of - you know, money, reparation for what you'd - the time lost.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did you belong to a trade union or professional organisation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes, we - I joined - I joined UDO you know, in -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Is it UNDO now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 That's right. That was - no. I joined in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13459625\charrsid13178822 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822  it}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13459625\charrsid13178822  was UDO,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
 I think so, it's always been called that. Shop assistant - no, but it didn't - they d
idn't used to be shop assistants did it, it used to be just Co-op. It used to be Co-op shops in the first place then they added shop assistants from - but I've been in it since about 19 - I don't think I was in it before I went in the Army. About 1920 I s
hould think I joined, 1920.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did you take part in any of its activities?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
No, not - only going to union meetings, I've been - used to go to union meetings. I only remember us once having a strike and it was before I was a member. It was - about - 
must have been my first year at Lane Ends and - and there were just - there was just a - a strike lasted about - not long, half a week I'd say.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Why weren't you a member at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 I'd only just started really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Weren't apprentices made members?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
Well I think they were, yes, I think they did but - somehow or other nobody bothered me. And - no, if - and I didn't - 'cos I never joined until I came out of the army, so nobody must have bothered me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did you feel at that time that workers and employers had the same interests or different ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
No, we of course - the - the employers as far as I - I was concerned was the manager of the shop, we hardly - we didn't come in touch with directors. There was the - the secretary you know, he was same.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Do you think you had similar interests?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 I didn't - I didn't come in contact with them much, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did you feel that there were divisions of interest among workers, some people say that in those days there was a great division betw
een trained craftsmen and other workers, did you fell that or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Well it doesn't apply much in shops does it. Not really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 I wondered if you'd see this looking at friends, relatives, neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Oh that sort of thing. Trained craftsmen we
re looked up too weren't they, I know - yes, I think so. Yes, anybody that - you might be getting a good wage but people used to think oh well he hasn't a trade, you know, and as soon as anything happens you used to lose your job didn't you. Yes. I think 
you - it was an asset to be a trained craftsman.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Would you say that full time work changed your general attitude to life in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Full time work? I don't think so Mrs - Cryer, 'cos you - you see, you grew up didn't you and if you - you got - 
you know, it was more or less - you've more responsibility like. You grew out of your childhood didn't you. And you sort of stand on your own feet a bit. But I don't think - you know, I can't remember any definite change of - outlook. I still kept up me m
o
ther interests you know, connected with the church and that, still carried on everything just as before, never went out of the village which made it more - difficult when I went in the Army. 'Cos we'd always lived in a quiet village you know, and then in 
a shop with only two or three people in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did you continue to live at home with your parents once you'd left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes. Yes. Until I was married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did starting full time work change your relationship with your parents at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Oh no. No
. I think it would be - I think me mother of course gave up working and - you know - always had - she always had - no, I don't think - things altered the relationships at all, no.;
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 What about your relationship with your brother, did you still continue to be friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
Yes. Yes. Yes, and he got - he became - he went to the mill in - in course of time he came to the age you know. And then he became an overlooker.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 And you were still connected with the church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes. Same people, friends, I had the same friends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 You still went to church and Sunday school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did you take an }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13459625\charrsid13178822 interested}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid818746\charrsid13178822  in politics at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Well when I got - I didn't much in - in the early days but when I came back - from the Army there was a - a new manage
r there, well I'd known him before but - he'd been conscientious }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2965629\charrsid13178822 objector}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
 during the war and - he was very interested in politics. And Labour politics. And - you know, I - I was very much influenced by him at that time. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 When was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 This
'd be after - this was when I came out in 1920. And I worked with this man until - until 1934. And I kept friends with him all - all me life you know. And he - he died a few - few years since. Used to - right down Station Road he died.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did you take an interest in politics at all before you went I - the army, the period before 1919?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 I don't think so, no, only very shallow I should think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Could you tell me what your views were then if you had any?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 You mean about political views? Oh I sho
uld think I should be Conservative then like me father, yes. Just because of father, I don't think I'd any deeper - because the war was on and everyone was watching the war and watching - hoping Lloyd George was the premier to help out, yes. But I hadn't 
any really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 You never had a vote at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 No. Not 'til I was - was it twenty-one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 You were never a member of a political party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 No, I - I've never been a member.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 You never worked for one of the parties at an election before 1919?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 You never took part in any political activity?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 You were never active politically at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 You told me earlier something of how you spent your spare time, mainly with the church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 You enjoyed walking and you did quite a bit of reading didn't you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did you continue to spend your spare time in the same way or did you do different things now that you'd started work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 No-, I don't think so we used to go dancing on Satu
rdays and - social life like that. Not - pictures or dancing. But mostly with the same people - set of people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did you make any new friends at all or did you stay with exactly the same crowd?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 I made a few more at the Co-op you now. That was a new circle. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 You'd one or two more friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Of your own age?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes, our own age group yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did you ever take your friends home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Well I did when I was married, yes. But to me mother's? Yes, we used to have - yes we used to take home - sometimes for Sunday tea, yes.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Did you have any special friends at this time, either boys or girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Oh as I grew older I had a special friend, yes. Yes, and of course he's dead now. And we kept -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 And you started going out with your wife quite young didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
Yes, that's right, and the two of us - they - they were friends. My - my friend's wife and Gladys and we - we - we ourselves - they got together and I did, that sort of worked itself out that way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 So the two boys and two girls sort of moved around together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Yes. That's right, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Would you go dancing and to the cinema with this group of friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 No, there was a group. There was a group of - of course, during the war - the evening services at 
church was - changed over to the afternoon for difficulty of blackout and the - the vicar at that time used to have a - we didn't like going, we wanted to get - an excuse to come out in the evening. So he arranged to - He had - we had a - a small service 
in the - in the school. And we - there was about - I suppose there was about - perhaps a dozen or fourteen of us and we'd all go walking round at the sing of a blackout. It was really - then some of the people told the vicar that it was just a -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Your 
younger sister died and your parents believed that it was as a result of being given dope when put out to nurse, do you remember them discussing it and what they said about this, about what they felt that }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13459625\charrsid13178822 dope'd}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822  been given?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 I never heard 'em say, you
 know, anything that she'd given - been given but - when they brought her home in the evenings after they come from work she - always tended to be sleepy and - they thought she'd been given some sort of dope or what they used to give them in those days I 
don't know. But I think - they said - they said she died of - they called it inflammation of the bowels so - but it - but it - what it actually was really A don't know. She was about eighteen months old.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 So they didn't actually specify what they thought it was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 
I never heard them saying anything beyond they - they just used that expression. Thought they'd given them something to keep 'em - put 'em to sleep during the day so they weren't any brother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 Your brother didn't start to walk until he 
was three, it couldn't have been at all that your mother had given him some sort of opium cordial perhaps similar to the dope that had been given to your sister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10167447 GW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 I doubt it. I shouldn't think, knowing me mother, I don't think she would. Unless - unle
ss it was given her by the doctor, something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid738450 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid818746\charrsid13178822 But you don't remember him being given anything?
